@Jonathan Towes Sure, but at what cost? The McNamara Fallacy a.k.a. the Quantitative Fallacy means attributing a greater weight to things that you can measure easily, ignoring all qualitative factors. What's the value of seeing a stranger smile? You have no clue. You can't measure it. You therefore assume that this it's value is approximately zero and can be ignored.

However, now you have a similar problem that you have with pollution except will an opposite sign. A small mutual benefit that you multiply by 330 million or even 7 billion is *not* small. 

Not to mention that you don't even know how many of these small but important things exist. Happily counting dead bodies and pretending that nothing else matters is a recipe for a strategic disaster.

